<p>Transparency International’s latest Corruption Perceptions Index (CPI) says anticorruption efforts are weakening in many democracies, and that the global average score has fallen to its lowest level in more than a decade. Other coverage points to notable drops in several Western countries once seen as relatively strong on governance, including the United States and the United Kingdom.</p><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>More Western slippage beyond the US and UK: Deutsche Welle points to Canada and Sweden, along with the United States and the United Kingdom, as countries whose CPI scores have fallen.</li><li>US and UK hit their lowest scores: Firstpost says both the United States and the United Kingdom have dropped to new lows on the index.</li><li>Political leadership matters: DW argues the backsliding it flags reflects, in part, a shortage of political leadership willing to prioritise anticorruption efforts.</li><li>How the watchdog puts it: The Straits Times says Transparency International calls the trend a “worrying decline” in democracies.</li></ul><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>Transparency International: The organisation says anticorruption efforts are declining across democracies worldwide. (<a href='https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2026/2/10/anticorruption-efforts-declining-in-democracies-around-the-world-watchdog'>Al Jazeera</a>)</li><li>Deutsche Welle analysis: DW casts the results as a warning for Western nations once seen as anti-graft leaders, arguing that thin political leadership is helping drive the backsliding. (<a href='https://www.dw.com/en/2025-corruption-index-flags-drops-in-western-nations/a-75838368'>Deutsche Welle</a>)</li><li>Firstpost report: Firstpost ties the declines it highlights—especially in the United States and the United Kingdom—to a run of political scandals. (<a href='https://www.firstpost.com/world/global-index-of-corruption-shows-steep-declines-as-us-uk-sink-to-new-lows-ws-e-13978159.html'>Firstpost</a>)</li></ul><h3>Sources:</h3><